{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540071"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:50:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16733"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16733"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.08,0.06,0.81,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9424"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66654"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9424"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16733"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11110"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66654"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting contraception. She smokes 15 cigarettes per day and has no significant medical history. She does not take any regular medications. Her parent died of a pulmonary embolism at age 45. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m2. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She prefers oral contraception and is reliable with taking daily medications. She declines long-acting reversible contraception as she is uncomfortable with implanted devices.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate statement regarding contraceptive options for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Combined oral contraceptive pill is safe to prescribe","All hormonal contraception is contraindicated","Progesterone-only pill increases risk of thromboembolism","Progesterone-only pill is a safe option","Progesterone-only pill is contraindicated due to smoking status"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has multiple risk factors for venous thromboembolism (VTE) including smoking, obesity (BMI 32 kg/m2), and family history. Understanding the thrombotic risk of different contraceptive options is crucial for safe prescribing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone-only pill is a safe option\u003C/strong\u003E as it does not increase the risk of VTE. Multiple studies have shown that progesterone-only contraceptives, including pills, implants, and intrauterine devices, do not increase thrombotic risk. They are therefore suitable for women with risk factors for VTE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill is safe to prescribe\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Combined hormonal contraceptives are contraindicated in this patient due to multiple VTE risk factors: age over 35 years with smoking, obesity, and family history of VTE. The oestrogen component increases thrombotic risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone-only pill increases risk of thromboembolism\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Unlike combined hormonal contraceptives, progesterone-only methods do not increase VTE risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone-only pill is contraindicated due to smoking status\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While smoking is a contraindication to combined hormonal contraceptives in women over 35 years, it does not contraindicate progesterone-only methods.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll hormonal contraception is contraindicated\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While combined hormonal contraceptives are contraindicated, progesterone-only methods remain safe and effective options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe World Health Organization Medical Eligibility Criteria for Contraceptive Use provides clear guidance: progesterone-only methods are category 1 (no restriction) or 2 (advantages generally outweigh risks) for women with VTE risk factors, while combined hormonal contraceptives are category 3 or 4 (risks outweigh benefits or represent unacceptable health risk).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Progesterone-only pills do not increase the risk of venous thromboembolism and are safe in women with risk factors for VTE.","Combined oral contraceptive pills are contraindicated in women with multiple risk factors for VTE.","Progesterone-only pills are a suitable contraceptive option for women who smoke and are over 35 years old.","Perfect use of progesterone-only pills has a failure rate of \u003C1%, but typical use has a 9% failure rate."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Contraception: Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2023 [cited 2024 Dec 1]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Contraception-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16733"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T17:58:51+10:30","updatedAt":"20